/*****UNEXPECTED BEHAVIORS*****/ 
(For clarification, this section explains how the program handles unexpected user input behaviors and not unexpected behaviors of the program itself -- this is described in AREAS WHERE p2 DOES NOT WORK)
For ambiguous output redirections such as echo hi > a >> b this is handled by checking in the child if the flags of both outputRedirectionFlag and the AppendFlag are set. If they are then The child outputs a message to stderr and exits. 

History input out of bounds: When the user inputs a number such as !11, then the program performs an atoi on '11'. If 11 was between 1 and 10 then it would have set a variable called successInput to 1. But since it is not, then successInput remains 0 and then a stderr is printed "History value out of range. Enter a number from 1 through 9.\n". Another case would be if the user inputted a number that does not exist yet. If the current prompt is %2% and the user inputted !5, then the program checks if the historyArray[5][0] != NULL. If it is null then the program has not gotten that far yet and successInput remains a zero. Since the value 5 is within the legal range however, it prints out a different message to stderr: " History value does not exist\n".

Multiple Pipes: As described earlier, each time parse() encounters a "|", a variable called pipeCharCount is incremented. This initial loop simply checks for metacharacters and increment a respected variable assigned to them. In the next loop, it performs more complex tasks (such as changing directories when "cd" is encountered).  In this next loop when "|" is encountered and the pipeCharCount is == 2 then it does not set the pipeFlag and instead prints a message to stderr: "Must only have one pipe.\n" The program then breaks out and waits for the next line or user input.

